{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2eca19d3-13fd-45d3-9c3b-abf83ac78bb4","content":"No repo-specific docs on this topic. Here's the general guidance for macOS:\n\n### Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`\n\n1. **Check for macOS-generated crash reports** — macOS automatically writes crash logs to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Look for a `.ips` or `.crash` file matching your process name.\n\n2. **Enable core dumps** before running:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Cores are written to `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n3. **Check if SIP blocks core dumps** — on modern macOS, System Integrity Protection may prevent core generation. You can verify with:\n   ```bash\n   csrutil status\n   ```\n\n4. **Use `lldb` to inspect the core**:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n5. **For richer .NET diagnostics**, set the environment variable before running:\n   ```bash\n   export DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1\n   export DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4   # full dump\n   ```\n   Note: with NativeAOT (no CoreCLR runtime), these variables have **no effect** — they rely on `createdump`, which isn't bundled. The `ulimit -c unlimited` + `/cores/` approach is your primary path.\n\n**TL;DR**: Set `ulimit -c unlimited`, reproduce the crash, then inspect `/cores/core.<pid>` with `lldb`. The macOS diagnostic reports (`~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`) also provide stack traces automatically.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"56774890-fcd9-4c1f-b137-8c3b8541fc4e","outputTokens":424,"requestId":"2C57:97105:1402C72:16CFB2B:69F94DDB"},"id":"aaa0de25-d2b0-4c53-84a3-0779080f1c72","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:54:46.359Z","parentId":"77c75228-7ea2-4e96-bdf5-dab4bfa0a165"}
